    <subfield code="a">Iron phosphate glass (IPG) has gained recent interest for use in encapsulating radioactive waste for long term storage. In this work, we investigate 5 different compositions of iron phosphate glass. We consider amorphous structures of 3 known crystalline phases: Fe 2+ <math altimg="si1.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mrow><msubsup><mrow><mtext>Fe</mtext></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msubsup></mrow></math> (P 2 O 7 ) 2 , <math altimg="si4.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mrow><msubsup><mrow><mtext>Fe</mtext></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msubsup></mrow></math> (P 2 O 7 ) 3 and Fe 3+ (PO 3 ) 3 , and structures of IPG (40 mol% Fe 2 O 3 and 60 mol% P 2 O 5 ), with 4% and 17% Fe 2+ ion concentrations.</subfield>
